'''HMS ''Bristol''''' was a 50-gun {{sclass-|Portland|ship of the line|0}} [[fourth-rate]] [[ship of the line]], built for the [[Royal Navy]] in the 1770s. She served as a [[flagship]] during the [[Battle of Sullivan's Island]], [[Charleston, South Carolina]] in 1776 during the [[American Revolutionary War]] and later participated in the 1783 [[Battle of Cuddalore (1783)|Battle of Cuddalore]] during the [[Anglo-French War (1778–83)|Anglo-French War of 1778–83]]. By 1787 the ship had been converted into a church ship. Converted into a [[prison ship]] in 1794, ''Bristol'' instead served as a [[hospital ship]] until she was [[ship breaking|broken up]] in 1810.

==Description==
''Bristol'' had a length at the [[gundeck]] of {{convert|146|ft|m|1}} and {{convert|119|ft|9|in|m|1}} at the [[keel]]. She had a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|40|ft|7|in|m|1}}, a [[Draft (hull)|draught]] of {{convert|15|ft|7|in|m|1}} at [[deep load]] and a depth of [[hold (ship)|hold]] of {{convert|17|ft|6|in|m|1}}. The ship's [[tonnage]] was 1,049 <small>{{fraction|9|94}}</small> tons [[Builder's Old Measurement|burthen]]. ''Bristol'' was armed with twenty-two 24-pounder cannon on her main [[gundeck]], twenty-two 12-pounder cannon on her upper gundeck, and four 6-pounder cannon on the [[quarterdeck]] and another pair on the [[forecastle]]. The ship had a crew of 350 officers and [[naval rating|ratings]].<ref>Winfield, pp. 403–04.</ref>

==Construction and career==
''Bristol'', named after the [[Bristol|eponymous port]], was ordered on 12 October 1768 to a design by [[John Williams (naval architect)|John Williams]]. The ship, however, was not [[keel laying|laid down]] until May 1771 at [[Sheerness Dockyard]] and was [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 25 October 1775. [[Ship commissioning|Commissioned]] that same month, she cost [[pound sterling|£]]23,440 to built and a further £3,574 to [[fitting out|outfit]].<ref>Winfield, p. 404</ref>

During the American War of Independence, she was [[Commodore (Royal Navy)|Commodore]] [[Sir Peter Parker, 1st Baronet|Sir Peter Parker]]'s flagship during the attack on [[Sullivan's Island]] on 28 June 1776 and was heavily damaged during the battle. Later in the war, she was stationed off [[Jamaica]], and fought at the Battle of Cuddalore. After 1794 she was used as a [[prison ship]] (lying in Gillingham Reach, in the County of Kent),<ref>The London Gazette, Numb. 15386. From Tuesday 14 July, to Saturday 18 July 1801. Page 868.</ref> and was broken up in June 1810 at Sheerness.<ref>Winfield, p. 405.</ref>

